few hours for you, though.

197
00:12:07,667 --> 00:12:09,458
Suzu-<i>san</i>!

198
00:12:30,250 --> 00:12:32,000
Suzuha!

199
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:34,750
Let's meet again, okay?!

200
00:12:34,750 --> 00:12:37,042
I'll stay strong until then!

201
00:12:37,042 --> 00:12:39,542
So you stay strong too--!

202
00:12:48,792 --> 00:12:50,625
Good luck...!

203
00:12:53,792 --> 00:12:56,708
We've just received word that
the space satellite on the roof

204
00:12:56,708 --> 00:12:59,542
of the Radio Building in
Akihabara has gone missing.

205
00:12:59,542 --> 00:13:05,292
Hey, do you think these
were <i>our </i>initials on this badge?

206
00:13:05,292 --> 00:13:08,375
Okabe's "O," Hashida's "H," Shiina's "S"...

207
00:13:08,375 --> 00:13:09,417
Oh!

208
00:13:09,417 --> 00:13:13,500
Then the "M" is for "Makise,"
and the "A" is for "Amane"!

209
00:13:13,500 --> 00:13:16,792
A lab member badge!
Wanna make one ourselves?

210
00:13:16,792 --> 00:13:17,917
Good idea!

211
00:13:17,917 --> 00:13:21,458
What's wrong, Okabe?

212
00:13:21,458 --> 00:13:25,125
The Divergence Meter's
number hasn't changed.

213
00:13:25,125 --> 00:13:30,917
Maybe it'll change after the present-day
Amane-<i>san </i>brings us the IBN 5100?

214
00:13:30,917 --> 00:13:34,292
Suzuha should be 54 now, right?

215
00:13:34,292 --> 00:13:38,208
My own daughter's over
three decades older than me...

216
00:13:38,208 --> 00:13:41,958
She could be married and
have grandchildren by now!

217
00:13:41,958 --> 00:13:45,125
I-In other words, I could
see my own great-grandkids

218
00:13:45,125 --> 00:13:46,542
while I'm still so young!

219
00:13:46,542 --> 00:13:51,667
You'll need to spoil them like
crazy, like a good great-grandpa!

220
00:13:51,667 --> 00:13:53,292
It's her!

221
00:14:04,375 --> 00:14:06,750
Mr. Braun?!

222
00:14:11,417 --> 00:14:13,042
A letter?

223
00:14:14,125 --> 00:14:16,583
Hashida Suzu...?!

224
00:14:16,583 --> 00:14:17,958
Could it be Suzu-<i>san</i>?!

225
00:14:17,958 --> 00:14:20,750
Seriously?! Then why is Mr. Braun...?

226
00:14:20,750 --> 00:14:24,208
That letter's from someone
who helped me out long ago.

227
00:14:24,208 --> 00:14:27,875
She asked me to give it
to you on this exact day.

228
00:14:27,875 --> 00:14:30,208
Where is she now?!

229
00:14:30,208 --> 00:14:32,000
She's dead.

230
00:14:34,333 --> 00:14:36,375
Died ten years ago.

231
00:14:39,292 --> 00:14:41,083
"Dear Okabe Rintaro...

232
00:14:41,083 --> 00:14:44,458
It's been a long while. This is Amane Suzuha.

233
00:14:44,458 --> 00:14:48,083
For you, it's probably
only a few hours since I left.

234
00:14:48,083 --> 00:14:52,417
It's currently June 13, 2000.

235
00:14:52,417 --> 00:14:54,583
I'll get straight to the point.

236
00:14:54,583 --> 00:14:56,583
I failed.

237
00:14:57,875 --> 00:15:01,750
I failed. I failed. I failed.

238
00:15:01,750 --> 00:15:08,333
I failed. I failed.
I failed. I failed. I failed.

239
00:15:08,333 --> 00:15:14,250
I failed. I failed. I failed. I failed.

240
00:15:14,250 --> 00:15:19,458
I only remembered
who I am a mere year ago.

241
00:15:19,458 --> 00:15:24,083
I had amnesia the 24 years before that.

242
00:15:24,083 --> 00:15:26,833
The time traveling didn't work right.

243
00:15:26,833 --> 00:15:30,167
The repairs were incomplete.

244
00:15:30,167 --> 00:15:35,167
But it wasn't your fault, Dad. It was mine!

245
00:15:35,167 --> 00:15:39,500
I should've just gone straight back to 1975.

246
00:15:39,500 --> 00:15:42,542
I should never have stopped by 2010!

247
00:15:42,542 --> 00:15:45,208
I shouldn't have been so selfish!

248
00:15:45,208 --> 00:15:48,542
The future won't change now!

249
00:15:48,542 --> 00:15:52,583
I couldn't get the IBN 5100.

250
00:15:55,000 --> 00:15:56,750
I'm sorry...

251
00:15:56,750 --> 00:15:58,958
I'm so sorry!

252
00:16:01,958 --> 00:16:06,583
Why did I even live to this age?

253
00:16:06,583 --> 00:16:10,417
I forgot my duty and
lived a carefree life instead!

254
00:16:10,417 --> 00:16:11,625
Forgive me!

255
00:16:11,625 --> 00:16:14,708
Forgive me! Forgive me! Forgive me!

256
00:16:14,708 --> 00:16:19,000
Okabe Rintaro, after that
time machine forum meeting,

257
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:23,083
you stopped me
from going back to 1975.

258
00:16:23,083 --> 00:16:24,667
You stopped me,

259
00:16:24,667 --> 00:16:29,625
and the thunderstorm that
night broke the time machine.

260
00:16:30,333 --> 00:16:36,375
If you can turn back time, I ask
that you don't stop me that day.

261
00:16:37,875 --> 00:16:39,833
My life...

262
00:16:39,833 --> 00:16:41,833
...was a waste."

263
00:16:53,542 --> 00:16:55,167
Mr. Braun.

264
00:16:55,167 --> 00:16:59,083
What do <i>you </i>want?
What's with the long faces?

265
00:16:59,083 --> 00:17:04,583
Please, tell me how Hashida Suzu-<i>san </i>died.

266
00:17:04,583 --> 00:17:06,667
What's it to you?

267
00:17:06,667 --> 00:17:10,083
I need to know how she died!

268
00:17:10,083 --> 00:17:15,458
I need to etch it into my mind,
no matter how it happened...!

269
00:17:16,875 --> 00:17:20,542
Sounds like it's more
than just simple curiosity.

270
00:17:20,542 --> 00:17:24,208
But what kind of relationship
did <i>you </i>have with Suzu-<i>san</i>?

271
00:17:24,208 --> 00:17:26,833
We were... old acquaintances.

272
00:17:26,833 --> 00:17:29,125
Very old.

273
00:17:29,125 --> 00:17:34,917
But even now I remember the time
we shared together like it was yesterday!

274
00:17:35,542 --> 00:17:38,375
I don't really wanna talk about it, but...

275
00:17:38,375 --> 00:17:40,292
...it was suicide.

276
00:17:40,292 --> 00:17:42,958
She hanged herself in her home.

277
00:17:44,500 --> 00:17:50,042
She'd been mentally unstable
the year leading up to it.

278
00:17:53,917 --> 00:17:59,167
But she'd always been a
cheerful, kind woman before then...

279
00:18:09,833 --> 00:18:11,792
It's my fault...

280
00:18:11,792 --> 00:18:17,958
The time machine broke
because I stopped Suzuha that night...

281
00:18:17,958 --> 00:18:23,958
If only I hadn't sent that D-mail,
she could've safely traveled to 1975!

282
00:18:23,958 --> 00:18:25,625
Okarin...

283
00:18:27,083 --> 00:18:30,250
Hold on, Okabe! What are you doing?!

284
00:18:30,250 --> 00:18:33,625
At this rate, Mayuri will end up...!

285
00:18:36,125 --> 00:18:39,792
You're sending a D-mail, Okarin?!

286
00:18:39,792 --> 00:18:43,083
It'll all disappear if you do that!

287
00:18:43,083 --> 00:18:44,542
I know...

288
00:18:44,542 --> 00:18:48,250
All the memories we made with
Suzu-<i>san </i>will never have happened!

289
00:18:48,250 --> 00:18:49,583
I know!

290
00:18:49,583 --> 00:18:55,042
So, please, change the future.

291
00:18:55,042 --> 00:18:56,917
Okarin!

292
00:19:06,917 --> 00:19:09,250
What do <i>you </i>want, Okabe?

293
00:19:13,042 --> 00:19:14,958
Hashida Suzu, huh...

294
00:19:14,958 --> 00:19:16,917
That name brings back memories.

295
00:19:16,917 --> 00:19:19,333
You knew her?

296
00:19:19,333 --> 00:19:20,708
Yes...

297
00:19:20,708 --> 00:19:23,167
Umm, do you know where she is now?

298
00:19:23,167 --> 00:19:26,583
It's been almost ten years now, I'd say...

299
00:19:26,583 --> 00:19:29,375
She really helped me out.

300
00:19:29,375 --> 00:19:33,042
I wish I could've at
least looked after her...

301
00:19:33,042 --> 00:19:35,333
It was a suicide, then?

302
00:19:35,333 --> 00:19:38,292
Huh?! A disease did her in!

303
00:19:38,292 --> 00:19:42,667
I live in her old house now!

304
00:19:45,750 --> 00:19:47,125
That bike...!

305
00:19:47,125 --> 00:19:51,750
Yeah. Suzu-<i>san </i>cherished it like crazy.

306
00:19:51,750 --> 00:19:56,083
I couldn't bring myself to throw it out,
so it's been sitting here for 10 years.

307
00:19:57,833 --> 00:20:02,042
At first, Suzu-<i>san </i>and
I were just regular neighbors.

308
00:20:02,042 --> 00:20:06,208
When I lost my house in a
fire--along with everything in it--

309
00:20:06,208 --> 00:20:11,000
she rented out a room here to me.

310
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:14,375
Was she all alone until then?

311
00:20:14,375 --> 00:20:17,000
I don't think she ever married.

312
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:20,208
She was an unusual woman.

313
00:20:20,208 --> 00:20:22,208
I once asked her why she was being so nice

314
00:20:22,208 --> 00:20:25,458
to a complete stranger she had no relation to.

315
00:20:25,458 --> 00:20:29,042
She smiled and answered with,

316
00:20:29,042 --> 00:20:33,375
"People's lives are a cycle
of helping and being helped.

317
00:20:33,375 --> 00:20:38,792
So someday you'll need to
help someone else yourself."

318
00:20:38,792 --> 00:20:41,750
Oh, yeah. Just a minute.

319
00:20:42,333 --> 00:20:45,250
This used to be Suzu-<i>san</i>'s.

320
00:20:45,250 --> 00:20:49,208
Do you know what the number means?

321
00:20:49,208 --> 00:20:53,083
When she was sick in bed, she
always gazed at this, saying things like,

322
00:20:53,083 --> 00:20:59,292
"Is this number before the change
or after the change? Did I change it?"

323
00:20:59,292 --> 00:21:03,083
It was always on her mind to the very end.

324
00:21:06,750 --> 00:21:09,917
The divergence number's changed.

325
00:21:10,917 --> 00:21:14,167
But it's still under 1%...

326
00:21:14,167 --> 00:21:18,042
The train on the outer loop
line will be arriving shortly.

327
00:21:18,042 --> 00:21:22,833
--Please stay behind the yellow line.
--The Yamanote Line is running now?!

328
00:21:22,833 --> 00:21:24,333
Mayuri!

329
00:21:28,792 --> 00:21:30,417
Damn!

330
00:21:36,875 --> 00:21:38,500
Mayuri!

331
00:21:47,958 --> 00:21:49,875
What's with you, Okarin?

332
00:21:49,875 --> 00:21:52,625
Nothing.

333
00:21:52,625 --> 00:21:57,750
Oh, Mayushii's phone was
ringing earlier. Was that you?

334
00:21:57,750 --> 00:22:01,458
She was so fast asleep I couldn't wake her up.

335
00:22:07,167 --> 00:22:09,375
Suzuha...

336
00:22:09,375 --> 00:22:12,583
Has the world changed now?

337
00:22:12,583 --> 00:22:16,792
Has Mayuri been saved now?

338
00:22:27,208 --> 00:22:35,167
<i>kisei sareta shikai mujihi naru</i>

339
00:22:36,167 --> 00:22:43,917
<i>juuni no shihai nogarerarenai</i>

340
00:22:43,917 --> 00:22:52,792
<i>ansoku no asu o negatta</i>

341
00:22:52,792 --> 00:23:01,500
<i>te no naka no toutoi jishou no chihei e</i>

342
00:23:01,500 --> 00:23:10,125
<i>torawareshi meiyaku</i>
<i>arawareta gishou no rinkaku</i>

343
00:23:10,125 --> 00:23:19,250
<i>seimei no tenchi wa</i>
<i>moumoku na jikan o kizanda</i>

344
00:23:19,250 --> 00:23:28,125
<i>habatake batafurai kiseki</i>
<i>no batafurai anata e sasagu</i>

345
00:23:28,125 --> 00:23:35,292
<i>namida no batafurai</i>
<i>mabushii batafurai subete ga</i>

346
00:23:35,292 --> 00:24:02,155
<i>ima kakikaerareru</i>

